The two Poles
The European Parliament recently condemned the Polish government's attempt to strip Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
Former leader of Solidarity, former political prisoner, and former foreign minister - who led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign yet another declaration stating that he was not an agent of the secret police during the communist era.
European parliamentarians spoke of a "witch hunt" regarding the behavior of the Polish government, and Geremek stated that the law on lustration [decommunization] constitutes a threat to public freedoms.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and inciting anti-Polish sentiment.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A decision by the constitutional court dated May 11 largely invalidated the lustration law, allowing Geremek to retain his seat in the European Parliament, at least for now.
But this law falls within the framework of a general policy of the Polish government whose only aim is to weaken the country's institutions and democratic fabric.
What is happening in Poland, the country where the collapse of communism began?
Every revolution goes through two phases: first, a struggle for freedom, then a fight for power.
The first is an emancipation of the human soul by which man expresses the best within him, while the second unleashes the worst: envy, intrigues, greed, suspicion, and the desire for revenge.
The revolution triggered by the Polish union Solidarity followed an unusual course.
Solidarity, forced into clandestinity when martial law was declared in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reemerge into the open in 1989, in the wake of the "perestroika" initiated by Gorbachev.
During the negotiations that ended the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached a compromise that paved the way for the peaceful dismantling of the communist dictatorship throughout the Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a compromising attitude rather than one of revenge, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a country divided between all-powerful winners and oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes in government, but the country has remained stable. The former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and the market economy.
But not everyone followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity revisionists, post-communist provincial agitators, xenophobic and antisemitic groups, heirs to pre-war chauvinism, and circles surrounding Radio Maryja, the voice of ethno-clerical fundamentalism.
One sees worrying signs everywhere: the authority of the Justice is being undermined, the independence of the Constitutional Court is being questioned, civil servants are being bought off, and the role of the prosecutor is being politicized.
Every day, social life undergoes repressive regulation.
Why all of this?
Every successful revolution has its winners and its losers.
The Polish revolution brought public freedoms, but also increased crime, a market economy, as well as the risks of bankruptcy for businesses and high unemployment, along with the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by a growing income gap.
She opened Poland to Europe, but she also induced fear of the foreign and fear of a mass invasion of Western culture.
For the losers of the Polish revolution of 1989, freedom comes with a lot of uncertainties.
In large companies, Solidarity workers have become the victims of the freedoms they have won.
In the communist prison universe, people were considered to belong to the state, but the latter took care of them.
In a world of freedom, there is no one to take care of us.
It is within this atmosphere of anxiety that the current coalition governs, combining the conservative potion of George Bush with the centralism of Vladimir Putin.
Solidarity veterans thought that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the firmament.
But the guilty among the communists were not punished, and the virtuous activists of Solidarity were not rewarded.
Also, the feeling of injustice gave rise to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed not only against former enemies but also against old friends who seemed to be coming out unscathed.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was Poland's greatest achievement in 300 years.
For them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland was in need of a moral revolution that would ensure crimes would not go unpunished, virtue would be rewarded, and injustices would be righted.
After their defeat in the 2005 general elections, the losing political parties chose a method: a major purge.
According to preliminary estimates, the purge should take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the archives of the security services; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people promised immunity must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make a false statement must be dismissed and prohibited from practicing their profession for ten years.
Sure! Please provide the French sentence you'd like translated into English.
Cardinal Dziwisz of Krakow reminds us that there is no place "for revenge, vengeance, disrespect for human dignity, and unfounded accusations."
Never since the fall of communism has a cardinal used such strong words.
Should this lustration have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The aim of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, not a hunt for suspects, proven or not, who had belonged to the secret police.
If this hunt had been organized in 1990, neither Leszek Balcerowicz's economic reforms nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would not be a member of NATO or the European Union.
Today, two Poles are facing each other.
The Poland of suspicion, fear, and vengeance fights the Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland - one of openness and tolerance, that of John Paul II and Czesław Miłosz, of my friends from the underground and from prison - must prevail.
I believe that the Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The decision of the constitutional court gives hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will not destroy either what gave it birth, the will for freedom, or what it has produced, a democratic state.
